answers.body_markdown:
One possible approach you can try.

Here the script **B.js** is loaded asynchronously. 

So, even before the script is loaded and executed, the JS code you have added in your html will run and throw `Uncaught ReferenceError: bng is not defined`.

    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;button id=&quot;btn_test&quot;&gt;Click Me&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;script&gt;
            // The below code will throw an error as it runs before B.js completes its execution and initializes window.bng()
            window.bng(&quot;btn_test&quot;);
        &lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;

In this case, we can define a function let&#39;s say `bng_test()` in **A.js** that&#39;s available on window before your application code executes


Make **A.js** synchronous and define the function `bng_test` in it.

    &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;script src=&quot;A.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
Application code can call this function `window.bng_test` defined in **A.js** instead of `window.bng` defined in **B.js**


Somewhere in **A.js**,  define an array (lets call it **event queue**) to store the calls from application until the actual function `window.bng` is ready.

 The new function `window.bng_test` will add items to the **event queue** if `window.bng` is not ready, else call `window.bng`

    const queue = [];
    window.bng_test = function(elementId) {
        // Check if the function bng is initialized
        if(window.bng){
          bng(elementId);
        }
        // Add the element to the queue
        else{
          queue.push(elementId);
        }  
    };

Now we could use a timer function to clear off the queue when **B.js** is executed and `window.bng` function is available.

      const interval = setInterval(() =&gt; {
        if (window.bng) {
          while (queue.length &gt; 0) {
            window.bng(queue.pop());
          }
          clearInterval(interval);
        }
      }, 500);

You might need to clear your timer on `window.beforeunload` as well to avoid memory leaks.

Pitfalls..

 - Script **B.js** is slow and user closes the window / navigated away,
   calls will be lost.
 - User has some calls in queue, **B.js** executed successfully, but
   user closed window / navigated away before timer clears the queue. In
   this case as well, you could make use of `window.beforeunload` to
   clear the queue.

